ce:section.ce:para:
To prove the applicability of the proposed analytical approach, commercial nutraceutical/dietary supplements with declared Q and nanoquercetin contents, as well as fresh vegetable samples (onion peels), were submitted to the developed methodology. Manufacturers of the Q nanoencapsulated supplements did not specify the theoretical droplet size of the nanoformulations, neither the amount of encapsulated Q. Furthermore, in the case of “One Planet Nutrition” product, its composition was not declared either. The pretreatment applied to these samples was described in the experimental section 2.5
                        . Firstly, their matrix effects were studied to assure no interferences in analytical measurements. Regarding those declared nanoquercetin-containing products, it was possible to visually appreciate that all Q was not really encapsulated. Then, it was necessary to separate by a centrifugation stage the encapsulated Q from the free one and from other potential aggregates; after that, the nanoquercetin size was evaluated by DLS (Table 3
                        ). From this study, it was found that Q-NEs size was greater than 100 nm for the One Planet Nutrition product in a variable range from 147 to 433 nm, while the size was less than 100 nm (92 nm) for the Actinovo one. Later, the content of both free or nanoencapsulated Q in all samples was quantified by the developed S,N-GQDs assisted fluorescence procedure.
